SIMPLE: refinement
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Refinement
<hw>Re*fine"ment</hw> <pr>(r?*f?n"m<it>e</it>nt)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>raffinement</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of
refining, or the state of being refined; <as>as, the <ex>refinement</ex>
or metals; <ex>refinement</ex> of ideas.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The more bodies are of kin to spirit in subtilty and
<qex>refinement</qex>, the more diffusive are they.</q>
<rj><qau>Norris.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From the civil war to this time, I doubt whether the corruptions
in our language have not equaled its <qex>refinements</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is refined, elaborated, or polished to
excess; an affected subtilty; <as>as, <ex>refinements</ex> of
logic</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>refinements</xex> of irregular
cunning.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Rogers.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Purification; polish; politeness; gentility;
elegance; cultivation; civilization.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Refiner</ent>⟦br⟧
